<module>
  <h>prepositions</h>

  <!--
  <p>Prepositions are word which typically describe <u>spaces</u> – both in the physical world, and
    in more abstract domains as well.</p>
  <hr/>
  <p>Prepositions govern an <u>object</u>, which must be a <a href="?xx=nouns/nouns">noun</a> in the
    dative.</p>
  <hr/>
  -->
  <p>The non-leniting prepositions are – <ul>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=a^preposition">--><g>à</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>out of</en> (elative)</li>
      <li><a href="?gd=aig"><g>aig</g></a>
        <en>at</en> (adessive)</li>
      <li><a href="?gd=air"><g>air</g></a>
        <en>on</en> (superessive)</li>
      <li><a href="?gd=an^preposition"><g>an</g></a>
        <en>in</en> (inessive)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=gu^preposition">--><g>gu</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>to</en> (allative)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=le">--><g>le</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>with</en> (instrumental)</li>
      <li><a href="?gd=ri"><g>ri</g></a>
        <en>at</en></li>
    </ul>
  </p>


  <!--
  <p>Apart from <strong>aig</strong> and <strong>air</strong>, these prepositions all have a special
    form in <strong>-s</strong> which is used before the definite article ie. <strong>às</strong>,
      <strong>anns</strong>, <strong>gus</strong>, <strong>leis</strong>, <strong>ris</strong>.</p>
      -->


  <p>The leniting prepositions are – <ul>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=bho">--><g>bho</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>from</en> (ablative)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=de">--><g>de</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>of</en> (partitive)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=do^preposition">--><g>do</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>into</en> (illative)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=fo">--><g>fo</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>under</en> (subessive)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=mu">--><g>mu</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>about</en></li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=ro">--><g>ro</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>before</en> (antessive)</li>
      <li><!--<a href="?gd=tro">--><g>tro</g><!--</a>-->
        <en>through</en> (perlative)</li>
    </ul>
  </p>


  <section>
    <h>dependents</h>
    <section id="complement">
      <h>complement</h>
      <p>Prepositions govern a noun complement in the dative case.</p>
      <p>Examples with inanimate objects (material location) – <xl>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha an cù <m>aig an dorus</m>.</gd>
            <tr>The dog is at the door.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 6</ref>
          </li>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha Seònaid a’ cluich <m>air an làr</m>.</gd>
            <tr>Janet is playing on the floor.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
          </li>
          <li>
            <gd>Nach eil Calum <m>anns an achadh</m>?</gd>
            <tr>Isn’t Malcolm in the field?</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 11</ref>
          </li>
        </xl>
      </p>
      <p>Examples with humans and animals – <xl>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha falt bàn <m>air Seumas</m>.</gd>
            <tr>James has fair hair.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 14 [adapted]</ref>
          </li>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha an cù còmhla <m>ri Calum</m> anns an achadh an diugh.</gd>
            <tr>The dog is along with Calum in the field today.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
          </li>
        </xl>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>uses</h>
    <section id="uses-pred">
      <h>predicate</h>
      <p>One common use of a preposition is to introduce the predicate of the verb <a href="?gd=bi"
            ><g>bi</g></a>
        <en>be</en>.</p>
      <p>Some examples involving material location – <xl>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha an cat beag bàn <m>aig</m> an teine.</gd>
            <tr>The little white cat is by the fire.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 9</ref>
          </li>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha gual <m>air</m> an teine.</gd>
            <tr>There is coal on the fire.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
          </li>
          <li>
            <gd>A bheil Seònaid <m>anns</m> an sgoil an diugh?</gd>
            <tr>Is Janet in the school today?</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
          </li>
        </xl>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="uses-comp">
      <h>complement</h>
      <p>A preposition can be used as the complement of an adverb.</p>
      <p>Some examples – <xl>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha an cù còmhla <m>ri</m> Calum anns an achadh an diugh.</gd>
            <tr>The dog is with Calum in the field today.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
          </li>
        </xl>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="uses-mod">
      <h>modifier</h>
      <p>A preposition can be used to introduce a locative modifier of a verb (or verbal noun).</p>
      <p>Some examples – <xl>
          <li>
            <gd>Có tha a’ cluich <m>air</m> an làr?</gd>
            <tr>Who is playing on the floor?</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
          </li>
          <li>
            <gd>Tha Màiri agus Calum ag obair <m>anns</m> an achadh.</gd>
            <tr>Mary and Malcolm are working in the field.</tr>
            <ref text="617">td. 6–7 [adapted]</ref>
          </li>
        </xl>
      </p>
    </section>

  </section>



  <!--
  <p>These prepositions all have a special form in <strong>-n</strong> which is used before the
